# REST Client / IntelliJ HTTP Client examples.
# Use the `npm run sign` helper to generate fresh X-Signature/X-Timestamp pairs:
#
#   npm run sign POST /v1/pos/transactions/authorize \
#     '{"terminalId":"T1","nsu":"0001","amount":"10.00"}'
#
# Then paste the headers below. They expire after HMAC_TIMESTAMP_TOLERANCE_SECONDS (default 300s).

@host = http://localhost:3000

### Health (no auth)
GET {{host}}/health

### Authorize a new transaction
POST {{host}}/v1/pos/transactions/authorize
content-type: application/json
x-correlation-id: demo-{{$timestamp}}
x-timestamp: <generate via npm run sign>
x-signature: <generate via npm run sign>

{
  "terminalId": "T1",
  "nsu": "0001",
  "amount": "10.00",
  "currency": "BRL"
}

### Confirm
POST {{host}}/v1/pos/transactions/confirm
content-type: application/json
x-timestamp: <generate via npm run sign>
x-signature: <generate via npm run sign>

{
  "transactionId": "01HY..."
}

### Void by transactionId
POST {{host}}/v1/pos/transactions/void
content-type: application/json
x-timestamp: <generate via npm run sign>
x-signature: <generate via npm run sign>

{
  "transactionId": "01HY..."
}

### Void by (terminalId, nsu)
POST {{host}}/v1/pos/transactions/void
content-type: application/json
x-timestamp: <generate via npm run sign>
x-signature: <generate via npm run sign>

{
  "terminalId": "T1",
  "nsu": "0001"
}
